Title: Barkskins
Author: Annie Proulx
My Review:
I really loved the first 25% or so of this book. I'm an Annie Proulx fan and it was evocative stuff - the chilly Boreal environment, the rough pioneers.

Then it all changed.

Generation after generation was introduced and exited. Normally I'm a fan of the epic generation-sweeping and continent-sweeping novel, but this descended into something more like bullet point lists of what each generation got up to until they died.

The tone lurched from novelised version of "a history of the forestry industry" to preachy "save the forest". In the end I thought perhaps we were about to see a bit of hope and optimism. But, no.

Too ambitious I think.
